12 WHEREAS, more than a century ago, hunters and anglers were among
13 the first conservationists who realized America’s natural resources
14 were in peril and could not sustain unregulated harvest and habitat
15 destruction; and
16 WHEREAS, sportsmen and women took it upon themselves to support
17 laws that stopped excessive harvest of fish and wildlife,
18 established state agencies to protect fish, wildlife, and their
19 habitats, and supported special fishing and hunting license fees to
20 help fund the new agencies’ efforts to provide healthy natural
21 resources for future generations; and
22 WHEREAS, the Oklahoma House of Representatives then and now
23 recognizes that the primary authority to protect and manage fish
24 within their state waters resides with the state agencies; and
HR1023 HFLR Page 1
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.
1 WHEREAS, upon realizing that license fees alone were
2 insufficient to restore and sustain healthy fish populations,
3 anglers supported excise taxes on fishing equipment to raise
4 additional funds to support restoration and enhancement efforts of
5 the state agencies; and
6 WHEREAS, the Sport Fish Restoration Program, which began 75
7 years ago with the passage of the Federal Aid in Sport Fish
8 Restoration Act in 1950 (further expanded with the Wallop-Breaux
9 amendment to the Sport Fish Restoration Act in 1984) is a vital part
10 of conservation funding in the United States; and
11 WHEREAS, a manufacturer's excise tax on fishing equipment, along
12 with an excise tax on motorboat and small engine fuels, is mostly
13 distributed back to the states through the U.S. Fish and Wildlife
14 Service for fisheries conservation, management, and angler and
15 boater access; and
16 WHEREAS, this cooperative partnership between the sportfishing
17 industry, anglers, boaters, the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service, and
18 state natural resource agencies has resulted in the most successful
19 model of fisheries management in the world, restoring and enhancing
20 populations across the United States and its territories; and
21 WHEREAS, since 1939, the combined contribution of the Sport Fish
22 Restoration Program and license fees to state fish and wildlife
23 agencies exceeds $78 Billion – more than any other single
24
